[2] Swollen shoot, cocoa - Ghana: control attempts
Date: Mon 12 Apr 2010
Source: Ghana Business News, Ghana News Agency (GNA) report [edited]
<http://www.ghanabusinessnews.com/2010/04/12/cocoa-farmers-refuse-to-destroy-disease-infected-farms/>


Cocoa farmers refuse to destroy disease infected farms
------------------------------------------------------
Most cocoa farmers in the Central Region whose farms have been infected
with the swollen shoot disease are refusing to allow the trees to be cut
down for fear of losing their farms to the land owners. When the land
becomes vacant, those who wish to re-crop have to enter into new
negotiations which, in most cases, do not go in favour of the farmer.
Therefore farmers prefer to continue to enjoy the little harvest from their
[diseased] trees.

Samuel Ankomah, Central Regional Cocoa Extension Officer, expressed dismay
about the refusal of the farmers to allow the destruction of their infected
cocoa farms for replanting. He said the situation could have adverse
effects on cocoa production in the country. He said the government had
earmarked money to be paid to farmers whose diseased cocoa trees were cut
down; free hybrid seedlings would also be supplied and technical advice
offered by extension workers. The Ghana Cocoa Board had nursed more than
1000 hybrid cocoa seedlings to be supplied to the affected farmers for
replanting.

