[3] Swollen shoot, cocoa - Ivory Coast: spread
Date: Fri 9 Apr 2010
Source: The Citizen [edited]
<http://www.thecitizen.co.tz/business/14-international-business/983-disease-to-cut-ivorian-cocoa-harvest-t-by-2pc>


Disease to cut Ivorian cocoa harvest by 2 per cent
--------------------------------------------------
Cocoa output from the world's top grower, Ivory Coast, will slip 1.9 per
cent during the 2009-10 season due to the effects of swollen shoot disease,
the West African nation's representative to the International Cocoa
Organisation, Saint-Cyr Djikalou, said.

He said the country's cocoa production has been falling in the past few
years mainly due to an attack by the swollen shoot disease, and some
farmers are switching to growing rubber to diversify their sources of
income. Ivory Coast cocoa output during the 2008-09 season reached just
over 1.22 million tonnes, the lowest output in at least 5 years. The
2009-10 crop would likely come in at 1.2 million tonnes, and output during
the 2010-11 crop could fall even further.

"The government and research partners have intensified efforts to contain
the spread of the disease and we are still waiting for the results," he
said. "But the way things are now, our output could drop to anything
between 1 and 1.1 tonnes next year [2010-11]."

[additional news story:
<http://234next.com/csp/cms/sites/Next/Money/5546218-147/cocoa_faces_farmers_exodus_into_rubber.csp>]

