[Coffee
-------
The 2 commercially grown coffee species are _Coffea arabica_ (arabica or
highland coffee) and _Coffea canephora_ (robusta or lowland coffee).

Coffee berry disease (CBD; also called green berry anthracnose) is caused
by the fungus _Colletotrichum kahawae_. CBD occurs only in Africa and
affects arabica coffee only with losses of up to 80 per cent. The pathogen
affects flowers, immature coffee berries, and sometimes the beans. Infected
berries display dark sunken spots coalescing into lesions. Berry
development may be arrested resulting in mummified berries on branches.
Infected berries are considered the major source of inoculum, and spores
are spread mainly by wind-blown rain or drops from tree tops. Disease
management includes cultural practices, quarantine, and periodic fungicide
treatments. Some resistant host cultivars exist, and more are being
developed. _C. coffeanum_ causes a similar disease in South America.

Coffee leaf rust (CLR; also called orange rust) is caused by the fungus
_Hemileia vastatrix_, one of the most feared pathogens of the crop. It also
affects only arabica varieties and has destroyed plantings in many
countries. The disease is characterised by yellow-orange powdery lesions on
the underside of leaves, where it attacks through stomata; it rarely occurs
on stems or fruit. Spores are spread by wind and rain. Disease management
relies mainly on multiple fungicide applications during the rainy season.
Rust-resistant cultivars exist, but the crop is generally of poorer
quality. More than 30 races of the fungus have been detected, making it
particularly difficult to establish durable host resistance.

Robusta varieties in Uganda are affected by coffee wilt disease (CWD, also
called tracheomycosis) caused by the fungus _Gibberella xylarioides_ (see
ProMED-mail post 20090514.1807).

Cocoa
-----
Swollen shoot disease of cocoa is caused by _Cacao swollen shoot virus_
(CSSV; genus _Badnavirus_) and can lead to severe crop losses. CSSV is
thought to have been transferred to cocoa from West African forest trees.
Symptoms vary with different viral strains from severe effects on shoots
and roots to no symptoms at all. The virus is spread by several species of
mealybugs (_Pseudococcidae_) and may also be transmitted by grafting and
mechanical inoculation. Seed transmission is also suspected.

Disease management relies on phytosanitation and clean plant material. Most
affected countries require the removal of all infected trees and their
neighbours. Mealybugs are difficult to control, and native forests serve as
pathogen reservoirs. Breeding programmes for virus- or vector-resistant
crop varieties have been initiated.

In Ghana, a westward spread of CSSV led to a serious outbreak in 2008 (see
ProMED-mail post 20081030.3416) with the possibility of the involvement of
a new viral strain. In 2008, Cote d'Ivoire launched a 2-year project to
fight swollen shoot (see ProMED-mail post 20080302.0860) including
replanting and rejuvenation programmes. However, doubts have been cast on
the CSSV resistance levels (at least under field conditions) of the new
hybrid varieties.

